  "texts": [
    "The prescribed Jacobian equataion is of interest in the Calculus of Variations and in elasticity, for which a standard reference is the book of Dacorogna [14,Chapter 14].",
    "Specifically in elasticity, a lower estimate on the Jacobian is a natural constraint, since zero Jacobian corresponds to compressing the underlying material infinitely, which would require infinite energy [6, (2.7)].",
    "In the recent work of Bevan et al [9] a constrained minimisation problem is studied and the constraint is given by the equation (1.1).",
    "Namely, a functional F(π) is minimised over vector fields π which solve the equation (1.1) for a fixed right hand side ρ.Then there is the link of the prescribed Jacobian equation to the theory of optimal transport (via the Monge-Ampère equation [4, Lecture 7]).",
    "Interestingly, optimal transport is also directly connected to metric currents -in particular (normal) metric 1-currents, which can be seen as transporting the positive part of their boundary to the negative part."
